revision.text:
{{Orphan|date=December 2012}}

The use of '''abusive language''' to another person is illegal in a small number of U.S. states.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20030514020600/http://leg1.state.va.us/cgi-bin/legp504.exe?000+cod+18.2-416 Commonwealth of Virginia code on abusive language] Retrieved 2011-10-14.</ref><ref>[http://law.justia.com/codes/mississippi/2010/title-97/35/97-35-11/ Mississippi code on abusive language] Retrieved 2011-10-14.</ref> Offenders are typically charged with this offense in conjunction with other crimes, such as [[aggressive driving]] or [[assault]]. However, in 1989 the [[New York State Court of Appeals]] ruled that abusive language was protected under the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution]].<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/62RVJkRas?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1989/12/20/nyregion/new-york-court-voids-law-on-abusive-language.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm Sam Howe Verhovek, "New York Court Voids Law on Abusive Language". ''New York Times'', December 20, 1989] Retrieved 2011-10-14.</ref>

