The '''7 · 4 South and North Korea Joint Statement''', also known as the '''July 4th North-South Joint Communiqué''', was signed on July 4, 1972, by the [[Republic of Korea]] and the [[DPRK]] government for the first time since the division of the Korean peninsula. In 1972, following the instructions of [[Park Jung-hee]], the director of KOREA-CIA [[Lee Hu-rak]] was sent to the Democratic People's Republic of Korea and met with [[Kim Il-sung]] to establish three principles of unification: 1) independence, 2) peace and 3) nation-wide unity. It was enacted to promote international detente, declaration of the withdrawal of the [[USFK]] and reduction of Military arms competition. However, after the discussion on unification, the regime of both sides of the two Koreas was unable to proceed with the real action plan because of the instability of their political power in the country. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archives.go.kr/next/search/listSubjectDescription.do?id=003345 |title= 7 · 4 South and North Korea Joint Statement |publisher=archives.go.kr |date= |accessdate=2017-08-25 |language= Korean}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://peacemaker.un.org/korea-4july-communique72 |title= The July 4 South-North Joint Communiqué |publisher=peacemaker.un.org/|date= |accessdate=2018-08-24 |language= English}}</ref> <ref> http://www2.law.columbia.edu/course_00S_L9436_001/North%20Korea%20materials/74js-en.htm}</ref>
